remarks.para:
Random values are generated using a lookup table. Since the table is limited, the noise
function repeats itself in each dimension after 256 values, for example:

Compute(x, y, z) == Compute(x + 256, y + 256, z + 256).

remarks.code:

double noise = 0;
for (int i = 0; i < numberOfOctaves; i++)
{
  double k = 1 << i;
  noise += 1.0 / k * PerlinNoise.Compute(k * x, k * y, k * z);
}

member.param:
When this method returns, the value associated with the specified key, if the key is found; 
otherwise, the default value for the type of the value parameter. This parameter is passed 
uninitialized.

